9.0.5
</code></pre>

# üêû bug report

### Is this a regression?

It used to work fine with Angular 8

### Description

Once we upgraded to Angular 9, we got this problem. We use Nx to organize the project, we I do not believe it has anything to do with it. We have one publishable Angular library and one Angular application. The library export a NgModule with a lot of components & pipes. `npm start` works as expected. However, building in production fails.

I do `ng build my-lib --prod`, which creates a dist version in `dist/libs/my-lib` by ng-packagr. For the production build of the application, we add a TypeScript path `@work/my-lib` => `dist/libs/my-lib`, i.e. we use the created output by ng-packagr. When I do `ng build my-app --prod`, then we get the following errors for __some__ of the components:

```
error NG6001: The class 'XXX' is listed in the declarations of the NgModule 'YYY', but is not a directive, a component, or a pipe. Either remove it from the NgModule's declarations, or add an appropriate Angular decorator.
```

The class is a very simple component with the appropriate attribute. We have probably 50 components and we get this error for only 7 of them. What makes it more weird is that the order of import in the module "solves" some of the errors. I.e., in my `lib.module.ts` we can change the order of such imports

```
import { MyComponent1 } from 'components/my-component1.component.ts';
import { MyComponent2 } from 'components/my-component2.component.ts';
```

and some of the errors disappear. I tried, of course, to solve it this way first, but I cannot "resolve" all 7 errors.

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction

I tried to reproduce this in a smaller set-up, but to no avail - with fewer components, it works well. So I hope you could point me to something, where I could give more information.

